## 5. ALB Target Group Issue with target-type IP

### Issue

ALB is created, but target group targets are unhealthy.

### Important Point

We are using:

    alb.ingress.kubernetes.io/target-type: ip

So ALB directly registers Pod IPs in the target group.

### Possible Reasons

- Pod is not ready
- Readiness probe is failing
- Service selector does not match pod labels
- Service targetPort is incorrect
- Target group health check path is wrong
- Application is listening on a different port
- Security group does not allow ALB to reach pod IPs
- VPC CNI networking issue
- Pod is restarting frequently

### Debugging Approach

I check:

- Pod status
- Pod readiness
- Service selector
- Pod labels
- Service endpoints
- Ingress health check path
- Application port
- ALB target group health
- AWS Load Balancer Controller logs

Commands:

    kubectl get pods -n <namespace> -o wide
    kubectl get svc -n <namespace>
    kubectl describe svc <service-name> -n <namespace>
    kubectl get endpoints <service-name> -n <namespace>
    kubectl get endpointslice -n <namespace>
    kubectl describe ingress <ingress-name> -n <namespace>
    kubectl describe pod <pod-name> -n <namespace>
    kubectl logs <pod-name> -n <namespace>

### Interview Answer

Since we use target-type IP, ALB directly registers Pod IPs. If targets are unhealthy, I check pod readiness, service selector, endpoints, health check path, application port, and security group rules. If endpoints are empty, mostly the service selector is not matching pod labels or pods are not ready.

